00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,001
A quadratic equation is a second-degree polynomial set to zero.

2
00:00:04,066 --> 00:00:07,509
Its standard form is a x squared plus b x plus c equals

3
00:00:07,609 --> 00:00:11,568
zero, where a, b, and c are coefficients, and a cannot be zero.

4
00:00:11,666 --> 00:00:13,714
The graph of a quadratic is a

5
00:00:13,814 --> 00:00:16,974
parabola. Its x-intercepts are called roots.

6
00:00:21,533 --> 00:00:25,168
The discriminant, Delta, equals b squared minus 4 a c.

7
00:00:25,266 --> 00:00:28,170
Its value determines the nature of the roots.

8
00:00:34,266 --> 00:00:37,196
The quadratic formula gives the roots directly.

9
00:00:38,266 --> 00:00:41,301
The plus-minus symbol accounts for both solutions, and

10
00:00:41,401 --> 00:00:43,913
the discriminant sits inside the square root.

11
00:00:48,466 --> 00:00:51,161
These are the roots. They solve the equation

12
00:00:51,261 --> 00:00:54,400
and are precisely the x-intercepts of the parabola.

